	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">psycopathicteen wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Is there any Command Prompt for dummies?</div><br />Windows Command Prompt is a clone of MS-DOS Command Prompt. The <em>very first</em> Dummies book was <em>DOS for Dummies</em> in 1991.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> I've been using the wrong slash key the whole time!</div>
<br />The DOS and Windows file system APIs accept both forward slash (/) and backslash (\) as folder separators, and a lot of programs will take both because they use the UNIX convention of starting options with a hyphen (-) (e.g. ls -l for list files in <strong>l</strong>ong format). But commands built into the command prompt (e.g. <strong>cd</strong>) and programs written by Microsoft (e.g. the Visual C++ compiler) assume / is only for options. This dates back to when MS-DOS 2.0 introduced folders. It used \ as the folder separator because / was already taken for command-line options, such as <strong>dir /s</strong> to list files in all <strong>s</strong>ubdirectories or <strong>dir /b</strong> to list in <strong>b</strong>are format with only filenames and not size or modification date. MS-DOS 2.0 tried to maintain compatibility with MS-DOS 1.0, which originally was a clone of Digital Research's CP/M, which also used / for command-line options.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


